From 754de13e02773f9c943689de9d77a4cfd154fa31 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Jake Teton-Landis <just.1.jake@gmail.com>
Date: Sun, 5 Jul 2026 04:08:05 -0400
Subject: [PATCH 17/25] Batch reporting is entanglement-aware: report the write
 set the pass consumed

A pass consumes updates from its ENTANGLED render lanes
(entangledRenderLanes = getEntangledLanes(root, lanes)), not just the
lanes that named the render. The registry ignored that: included-batches
came from the raw render lanes, and the finish edge classified a lane as
pruned whenever it left pendingLanes without being in the committed
lanes mask. Under sibling-transition entanglement (a second transition
writing through a hook queue that already holds the first's pending
update) the committing pass folds BOTH batches into the committed view
while the channel reported only one -- and retired the other
committed=false, a batch whose write the committed tree visibly shows.
With enableParallelTransitions (on by default in www test runs) this is
the COMMON shape, which is how the www runs enabled by the previous
commit caught it; on OSS channels the same shape arises whenever the
first transition is suspended when the second one schedules.

Fix, mirroring React's own bookkeeping exactly:
- batchTokensForRender expands its lanes with getEntangledLanes -- the
  same expansion prepareFreshStack assigns to entangledRenderLanes.
- commitRoot captures getEntangledLanes(root, lanes) BEFORE
  markRootFinished clears the entanglement bookkeeping and hands that to
  the finish edge as the committed mask. Safe: only slots whose lane
  actually left pendingLanes are considered, so entanglements that grew
  after the render (updates still pending) filter themselves out; and no
  same-root commit can have intervened since the pass rendered (it would
  have discarded the pass -- the S2 serialization proofs), so the
  expansion is the render-time one.

New test (ReactFiberExternalRuntimeCommit): two sibling transitions,
separate lanes/tokens, entangled through a shared useState queue; the
committing pass must include both tokens, the commit delta must carry
both, both retire committed=true, and resolving the first transition's
abandoned suspension afterwards is a no-op. Discriminating on www
(fails without the fix); on OSS channels it pins the grouped-render
equivalent of the same closure fact.

Fork suite: 18/18 on default and www-modern at this commit.
